Introduction

The mental health and well-being of students play a critical role in their academic performance and overall success. This data analysis project focuses on exploring the effects of mental health status on college studentâs GPA and academic success, as well as the impact of alcohol consumption on high school studentâs grades. By identifying patterns and correlations between these attributes, the study aims to look at key factors that may affect a studentâs ability to succeed academically. Beyond mental health and alcohol use, additional variables such as home life, parental success, and marital status will also be examined to provide a more comprehensive understanding of the factors influencing academic performance.

The findings from this analysis have the potential to benefit institutions that prioritize student well-being and academic success. High schools and colleges can utilize these insights to improve existing support systems and develop new interventions that address the specific needs of their students. Organizations that focus on youth mental health and substance abuse, such as On Our Sleeves, The Steve Fund, the Annie E. Casey Foundation, and the Child Mind Institute, may also find these results valuable. These groups work to support diverse youth populations, including individuals from economically disadvantaged backgrounds, students with learning barriers, and young people of color. Additionally, organizations like the National Institute of Drug Abuse could utilize this research to improve their efforts in reducing substance abuse among youth.

Ultimately, this project seeks to inform and enhance the programs and initiatives that support studentsâ mental health and well-being. By investigating how various factors influence academic success, the findings can help the development of updated outreach strategies and interventions to address mental health and substance abuse challenges. With this knowledge, educational institutions, health-focused organizations, and policymakers can better equip students of all ages to overcome barriers and thrive academically and personally.

Previous Work

Article 1: Association between mental health and academic performance among university undergraduates: The interacting role of lifestyle behaviors

https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9976597/

This is a study investigating how GPA is affected by mental health in university students, based on a survey on Japanese university students. This study is very similar to what we wish to explore with how the mental health state of university students affects their grades, opposed to GPA, based on a variety of factors. One major difference is that the mental health of the students is measured on a psychological scale, while our study uses data with binary indicators for several mental health conditions. In addition, we aim to develop predictive and interpretation models to further understand patterns between student grades and mental health

Article 2: Study: Inverse relationship between alcohol abuse and college GPA (PennState)

https://www.psu.edu/news/student-affairs/story/study-inverse-relationship-between-alcohol-abuse-and-college-gpa

This article discusses a report investigating alcohol abuse in university students, and how it affects GPA. Similar to what our analysis aims to investigate, the study outlined in the article finds a strong link between frequent binge drinking episodes and lower GPAs, and takes into account the studentsâ mental health. This article does not outline the statistical methods used in the study, but it appears that there also was no model development between GPA and alcohol abuse, which we plan to develop and explore. Another major difference is that the data used in this report was collected from university students at Penn State, and the data we are using in our exploration is from secondary/high school aged students in Portugal. However, both data were collected in 2008.

# Data Cleaning
MH_clean <- MH %>% 
  mutate( Gender = as.factor(`Choose your gender`),
          Course = as.factor(`What is your course?`),
          Year = as.factor(`Your current year of Study`),
          CGPA = as.factor(`What is your CGPA?`),
          Marital_Status = as.factor(`Marital status`),
          Depression = as.factor(`Do you have Depression?`),
          Anxiety = as.factor(`Do you have Anxiety?`), 
          Panic_Attacks = as.factor(`Do you have Panic attack?`),
          Treatment = as.factor(`Did you seek any specialist for a treatment?`),
          Year = ifelse(Year == "year 1", 1,
                        ifelse(Year == "Year 1", 1,
                        ifelse(Year == "year 2", 2,
                        ifelse(Year == "Year 2", 2,
                        ifelse(Year == "year 3", 3,
                        ifelse(Year == "Year 3", 3,
                               ifelse(Year== "year 4", 4, 4))))))),
          
          GPA_midpoint = ifelse(CGPA == "0 - 1.99", 1,
                                ifelse(CGPA == "2.00 - 2.49", 2.25,
                                ifelse(CGPA == "2.50 - 2.99", 2.75,
                                ifelse(CGPA == "3.00 - 3.49", 3.25, 3.75))))
          )%>%
  dplyr::select(-Timestamp, -`Choose your gender`, -`What is your course?`, -`Your current year of Study`,
                -`What is your CGPA?`, -`Marital status`, -`Do you have Depression?`,
                -`Do you have Anxiety?`, -`Do you have Panic attack?`, 
                -`Did you seek any specialist for a treatment?`)

The three bar charts shown above describe the relationship between anxiety and various different factors. These factors include GPA categories, gender, and year in school. The proportion of individuals reporting anxiety (âYesâ) is represented in teal, while those who do not report anxiety (âNoâ) are shown in red. In the first graph, examining proportions of anxiety within GPA categories, there appears to be an increasing trend amongst the proportion of students experiencing anxiety and GPA categories. Students in the 0â1.99 GPA range report the lowest proportion of anxiety, while those in higher GPA categories, particularly 3.00â4.00, show a larger share of anxiety. The low reporting of anxiety could be a result of low numbers of survey participants that fall into these GPA categories. The second graph reveals the proportions of anxiety across gender groups. Both male and female students report similar proportions of anxiety, with slightly higher anxiety levels among females. This minor difference could indicate that anxiety is a concern across genders, though females might experience or report it at marginally higher rates. The third graph shows anxiety proportions across the year in school. Anxiety levels remain relatively consistent across all four years, with no large differences. This stability might suggest that anxiety is a persistent issue throughout studentsâ academic journeys, unaffected by the year in school.

Mental Health Dataset

Code 
mh_recipe <- recipe(GPA_midpoint ~ Gender + Year + Marital_Status + Depression + Anxiety + 
                      Panic_Attacks + Treatment, 
                    data = MH_clean) %>%
  step_dummy(all_nominal_predictors()) %>% 
  step_normalize(all_numeric_predictors())
Code 
knn_mod_tune <- nearest_neighbor(neighbors = tune()) |>
  set_engine("kknn") |>
  set_mode("regression")
Code 
knn_workflow <- workflow() %>%
  add_model(knn_mod_tune) %>%
  add_recipe(mh_recipe)

mh_cvs <- vfold_cv(MH_clean, v = 5, strata = GPA_midpoint)
Code 
knn_grid <- grid_regular(neighbors(range = c(1, 20)), levels = 20)

set.seed(123)
knn_tune_results <- tune_grid(
  knn_workflow,
  resamples = mh_cvs,
  grid = knn_grid
)
Code

  collect_metrics() |>
  filter(.metric == "rmse") |>

First, we fit a KNN model to each dataset. For the mental health dataset, the target variable was Cumulative Grade Point Average of each student. The predictors we used in the model were all of them, so Gender, year of study, marital status, depression, anxiety, panic attacks, and seeking specialist treatment.

After tuning the model, we found that the optimal number of neighbors was 4. We based this decision on the metric that produced the highest RÂ². After fitting the model to the full data, we achieved an RÂ² of 0.251, which suggests that the model explains about 25.1% of the variance in GPA, leaving a substantial portion unexplained. The RMSE was 0.505, which is fairly low, but it could also be due to the dataset having a small number of observations.

For the Alcohol Consumption and Final Grade dataset, we also used KNN regression, with the target variable being the final grade. Predictors included age, daily and weekend alcohol consumption, absences, frequency of going out, previous failures, and study time.

After tuning the model, we found that the optimal number of neighbors for this recipe was 48. We based this decision on the metric that produced the highest RÂ². The modelâs RMSE was 2.68, and the RÂ² was 0.343, indicating that the predictors accounted for around 34.3% of the variance in final grades. If we include interaction, these metrics may go up.

We also fit a decision tree model to the mental health dataset. As previously mentioned, the target variable was the cumulative GPA of each student and we used gender, year of study, marital status, depression, anxiety, panic attacks, and seeking specialist treatment as predictors.

The model outputs a fairly simple decision tree, and it does not use 3 of the 5 GPA intervals in the data. There are very few observations in the two lowest GPA intervals, which is most likely why the tree decided to omit these classes. About 44% of the data is classified into the 3.00-3.49 range, and the other 56% is classified into the 3.50-4.00 range.

However, this is not an ideal model to represent the factors that influence GPA in students, as it only classifies students into a 3.00 to 4.00 range. The data may be better represented using bagged trees or random forests, or by assigning each observation to the median GPA value of the range and conduct regression opposed to this classification method. Based on these initial results, the next steps include refining the selection of predictors, exploring non-linear relationships, and testing more models, as we aim to improve our performance metrics.

# Introduction

The mental health and well-being of students play a critical role in their academic performance and overall success. This data analysis project focuses on exploring the effects of mental health status on college student's GPA and academic success, as well as the impact of alcohol consumption on high school student's grades. By identifying patterns and correlations between these attributes, the study aims to look at key factors that may affect a studentâs ability to succeed academically. Beyond mental health and alcohol use, additional variables such as home life, parental success, and marital status will also be examined to provide a more comprehensive understanding of the factors influencing academic performance.

The findings from this analysis have the potential to benefit institutions that prioritize student well-being and academic success. High schools and colleges can utilize these insights to improve existing support systems and develop new interventions that address the specific needs of their students. Organizations that focus on youth mental health and substance abuse, such as On Our Sleeves, The Steve Fund, the Annie E. Casey Foundation, and the Child Mind Institute, may also find these results valuable. These groups work to support diverse youth populations, including individuals from economically disadvantaged backgrounds, students with learning barriers, and young people of color. Additionally, organizations like the National Institute of Drug Abuse could utilize this research to improve their efforts in reducing substance abuse among youth.

Ultimately, this project seeks to inform and enhance the programs and initiatives that support students' mental health and well-being. By investigating how various factors influence academic success, the findings can help the development of updated outreach strategies and interventions to address mental health and substance abuse challenges. With this knowledge, educational institutions, health-focused organizations, and policymakers can better equip students of all ages to overcome barriers and thrive academically and personally.

https://www.psu.edu/news/student-affairs/story/study-inverse-relationship-between-alcohol-abuse-and-college-gpa

This article discusses a report investigating alcohol abuse in university students, and how it affects GPA. Similar to what our analysis aims to investigate, the study outlined in the article finds a strong link between frequent binge drinking episodes and lower GPAs, and takes into account the studentsâ mental health. This article does not outline the statistical methods used in the study, but it appears that there also was no model development between GPA and alcohol abuse, which we plan to develop and explore. Another major difference is that the data used in this report was collected from university students at Penn State, and the data we are using in our exploration is from secondary/high school aged students in Portugal. However, both data were collected in 2008.

```{r}
MH_clean <- MH %>% 
  mutate( Gender = as.factor(`Choose your gender`),
          Course = as.factor(`What is your course?`),
          Year = as.factor(`Your current year of Study`),
          CGPA = as.factor(`What is your CGPA?`),
          Marital_Status = as.factor(`Marital status`),
          Depression = as.factor(`Do you have Depression?`),
          Anxiety = as.factor(`Do you have Anxiety?`), 
          Panic_Attacks = as.factor(`Do you have Panic attack?`),
          Treatment = as.factor(`Did you seek any specialist for a treatment?`),
          Year = ifelse(Year == "year 1", 1,
                        ifelse(Year == "Year 1", 1,
                        ifelse(Year == "year 2", 2,
                        ifelse(Year == "Year 2", 2,
                        ifelse(Year == "year 3", 3,
                        ifelse(Year == "Year 3", 3,
                               ifelse(Year== "year 4", 4, 4))))))),
          
          GPA_midpoint = ifelse(CGPA == "0 - 1.99", 1,
                                ifelse(CGPA == "2.00 - 2.49", 2.25,
                                ifelse(CGPA == "2.50 - 2.99", 2.75,
                                ifelse(CGPA == "3.00 - 3.49", 3.25, 3.75))))
          )%>%
  dplyr::select(-Timestamp, -`Choose your gender`, -`What is your course?`, -`Your current year of Study`,
                -`What is your CGPA?`, -`Marital status`, -`Do you have Depression?`,
                -`Do you have Anxiety?`, -`Do you have Panic attack?`, 
                -`Did you seek any specialist for a treatment?`)
```

The three bar charts shown above describe the relationship between anxiety and various different factors. These factors include GPA categories, gender, and year in school. The proportion of individuals reporting anxiety ("Yes") is represented in teal, while those who do not report anxiety ("No") are shown in red. In the first graph, examining proportions of anxiety within GPA categories, there appears to be an increasing trend amongst the proportion of students experiencing anxiety and GPA categories. Students in the 0â1.99 GPA range report the lowest proportion of anxiety, while those in higher GPA categories, particularly 3.00â4.00, show a larger share of anxiety. The low reporting of anxiety could be a result of low numbers of survey participants that fall into these GPA categories. The second graph reveals the proportions of anxiety across gender groups. Both male and female students report similar proportions of anxiety, with slightly higher anxiety levels among females. This minor difference could indicate that anxiety is a concern across genders, though females might experience or report it at marginally higher rates. The third graph shows anxiety proportions across the year in school. Anxiety levels remain relatively consistent across all four years, with no large differences. This stability might suggest that anxiety is a persistent issue throughout students' academic journeys, unaffected by the year in school.

# Preliminary Results

## Mental Health Dataset

```{r}
mh_recipe <- recipe(GPA_midpoint ~ Gender + Year + Marital_Status + Depression + Anxiety + 
                      Panic_Attacks + Treatment, 
                    data = MH_clean) %>%
  step_dummy(all_nominal_predictors()) %>% 
  step_normalize(all_numeric_predictors())
```

```{r}
knn_mod_tune <- nearest_neighbor(neighbors = tune()) |>
  set_engine("kknn") |>
  set_mode("regression")
```

```{r}
knn_workflow <- workflow() %>%
  add_model(knn_mod_tune) %>%
  add_recipe(mh_recipe)

mh_cvs <- vfold_cv(MH_clean, v = 5, strata = GPA_midpoint)
```

```{r}
knn_grid <- grid_regular(neighbors(range = c(1, 20)), levels = 20)

set.seed(123)
knn_tune_results <- tune_grid(
  knn_workflow,
  resamples = mh_cvs,
  grid = knn_grid
)
```

```{r}
knn_tune_results |> 
  collect_metrics() |>
  filter(.metric == "rmse") |>
  slice_min(mean, n = 3)

knn_tune_results |> 
  collect_metrics() |>
  filter(.metric == "rsq") |>
  slice_max(mean, n = 3)
```

```{r}
knn_mod_best <- nearest_neighbor(neighbors = 4) |>
  set_mode("regression") |> 
  set_engine("kknn")
```

```{r}
best_workflow <- workflow() |>
  add_recipe(mh_recipe) |>
  add_model(knn_mod_best)

best_fit <- best_workflow |>
  fit(MH_clean) 

best_fit |> 
  extract_fit_parsnip()
```

```{r}
predictions <- predict(best_fit, new_data = MH_clean) %>%
  bind_cols(MH_clean)

regression_metrics <- predictions %>%
  metrics(truth = GPA_midpoint, estimate = .pred)

print(regression_metrics)
```

```{r}
MH_recipe1 <- recipe(CGPA ~ ., data = MH_clean) %>%
```

```{r}
knn_workflow <- workflow() %>%
```

```{r}

  collect_metrics() |>
  filter(.metric == "rmse") |>

  filter(.metric == "rsq") |>
  slice_max(mean, n = 3)
```

```{r}
knn_mod_best <- nearest_neighbor(neighbors = 48) |>
  set_mode("regression") |> 
  set_engine("kknn")
```

```{r}
best_workflow <- workflow() |>
  add_recipe(alc_rec) |>
  add_model(knn_mod_best)

best_fit <- best_workflow |>
  fit(Alc_clean) 

best_fit |> 
  extract_fit_parsnip()
```

```{r}
predictions <- predict(best_fit, new_data = Alc_clean) %>%
  bind_cols(Alc_clean)

regression_metrics <- predictions %>%
  metrics(truth = Final_Grade, estimate = .pred)

print(regression_metrics)
```

First, we fit a KNN model to each dataset. For the mental health dataset, the target variable was Cumulative Grade Point Average of each student. The predictors we used in the model were all of them, so Gender, year of study, marital status, depression, anxiety, panic attacks, and seeking specialist treatment.

After tuning the model, we found that the optimal number of neighbors was 4. We based this decision on the metric that produced the highest RÂ². After fitting the model to the full data, we achieved an RÂ² of 0.251, which suggests that the model explains about 25.1% of the variance in GPA, leaving a substantial portion unexplained. The RMSE was 0.505, which is fairly low, but it could also be due to the dataset having a small number of observations.

For the Alcohol Consumption and Final Grade dataset, we also used KNN regression, with the target variable being the final grade. Predictors included age, daily and weekend alcohol consumption, absences, frequency of going out, previous failures, and study time.

After tuning the model, we found that the optimal number of neighbors for this recipe was 48. We based this decision on the metric that produced the highest RÂ². The model's RMSE was 2.68, and the RÂ² was 0.343, indicating that the predictors accounted for around 34.3% of the variance in final grades. If we include interaction, these metrics may go up.

We also fit a decision tree model to the mental health dataset. As previously mentioned, the target variable was the cumulative GPA of each student and we used gender, year of study, marital status, depression, anxiety, panic attacks, and seeking specialist treatment as predictors.

The model outputs a fairly simple decision tree, and it does not use 3 of the 5 GPA intervals in the data. There are very few observations in the two lowest GPA intervals, which is most likely why the tree decided to omit these classes. About 44% of the data is classified into the 3.00-3.49 range, and the other 56% is classified into the 3.50-4.00 range.

However, this is not an ideal model to represent the factors that influence GPA in students, as it only classifies students into a 3.00 to 4.00 range. The data may be better represented using bagged trees or random forests, or by assigning each observation to the median GPA value of the range and conduct regression opposed to this classification method. Based on these initial results, the next steps include refining the selection of predictors, exploring non-linear relationships, and testing more models, as we aim to improve our performance metrics.
